01:01:02.080 --> 01:01:08.479
One question that came up earlier, I just want to make sure to ask was around like,

01:01:08.479 --> 01:01:13.040
what does a technical interview look like for your team or how do you approach interviews?

01:01:13.840 --> 01:01:20.800
Yeah. So we've, I've tried to do different iterations on this, but the one I'm

01:01:20.800 --> 01:01:24.479
currently using right now, and again, this is evolving over time and I'm sure there's

01:01:24.479 --> 01:01:30.879
better ways to do it. Like my personal opinion is like hiring is so difficult that I don't think

01:01:30.879 --> 01:01:36.239
any of us are trained in that. I don't know if there is training. So we're all doing our best

01:01:36.800 --> 01:01:44.560
in a complicated process. But for me, what I, what I boil it down to is like, can you do what

01:01:44.560 --> 01:01:50.800
you say you can do, right? I need to have some sort of test that shows me that you can do what you

01:01:52.080 --> 01:01:58.800
say you can do. So it doesn't need to be any more complicated or intensive than that. And I'll give

01:01:58.800 --> 01:02:03.679
you, I'll give everybody an example. So not this time, but last time I hired, I got to a second

01:02:03.760 --> 01:02:09.600
interview with a group of people and I had a coding challenge that I gave people, I don't know,

01:02:09.600 --> 01:02:14.239
24 or 36 hours or something to do, return it back to me. And there's a variety of reasons why I do

01:02:14.239 --> 01:02:20.320
that. I got down to the time I was supposed to speak with this individual and he, the person

01:02:20.320 --> 01:02:27.760
sent me an email one hour in advance and just said, I have nothing. I could not do the exercise.

01:02:27.760 --> 01:02:33.600
I told you I could do X, Y, Z, and either I overestimated myself or I, you know, he didn't

01:02:33.600 --> 01:02:40.399
say he was lying, but he basically couldn't do what he said he could do. So I avoided a very large

01:02:40.399 --> 01:02:46.560
and costly mistake. Had I gone on to just trust that person and I'm not saying it was done

01:02:46.560 --> 01:02:50.719
intentionally or that this person was trying to fool me, but I'm just saying we have to have some

01:02:50.719 --> 01:02:54.959
sort of checks and balances that people could do what they say they can do. Right. And then I just

01:02:54.959 --> 01:03:02.560
want to see the depth of your work. Like how far do you take things down? Are you just a simple,

01:03:03.120 --> 01:03:06.560
add two numbers together? No, that's fine. We'll get to that in a second.

01:03:07.199 --> 01:03:12.239
But do, can you show me some techniques that I think that you could bring to the table? Right.

01:03:12.239 --> 01:03:18.000
And then the third component of that is there's no perfect candidate and everybody's going to come

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:22.560
in with their different strengths and weaknesses. Right. And by doing this coding challenge,

01:03:23.199 --> 01:03:28.320
I'm learning about you as a candidate to say, where do I need to upscale this person? Where do

01:03:28.320 --> 01:03:32.879
I need to spend time with this person on day one, prior to this person starting, I'm going to have

01:03:32.879 --> 01:03:38.479
a plan. I'm going to say this person needs to get better in XYZ or after a certain number of months,

01:03:38.479 --> 01:03:43.360
I want to circle back with them and say, Hey, I think you can utilize these skills a little bit

01:03:43.360 --> 01:03:49.199
better and make you more efficient or can excel your code writing ability or whatever it might be.

01:03:49.760 --> 01:03:54.080
Or maybe it's somebody on my team, like, Hey, this person on my team, I think would really help you

01:03:54.080 --> 01:03:59.679
in this area. So by showing me a little bit about what you can do, that's not to eliminate you as a

01:03:59.679 --> 01:04:02.639
candidate. It's more or less to see what are your strengths? What are your weaknesses? How can I

01:04:02.639 --> 01:04:11.760
help you? How can I upscale to you eventually? Thank you, Ian. That's really helpful. I know

01:04:11.760 --> 01:04:16.959
that comes up quite a bit in terms of like technical interviews. And sometimes when people

01:04:16.959 --> 01:04:24.560
are asking maybe far too much of someone, we need to make sure that they have that component.

01:04:24.560 --> 01:04:29.040
Yeah, I've read the, you know, the tech world is in the whiteboarding and all that stuff and

01:04:29.040 --> 01:04:38.159
putting people. I don't think that's for me, coming from a sport background, the whole idea

01:04:38.239 --> 01:04:47.600
of practice in sport is to simulate things that you will see in a game, because that's your job,

01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:53.040
to play games. So if we expect you to perform at a high level in a game, we need to simulate that

01:04:53.040 --> 01:04:59.600
situation, slow it down, help you practice and get better and get the synapses moving quickly

01:04:59.600 --> 01:05:04.080
and firing quickly, right? That's the whole idea of practice is to slow things down and then

01:05:04.080 --> 01:05:08.159
gradually build up and up and up and translate exactly what you did in practice into a game.

01:05:08.159 --> 01:05:11.120
If I'm having you do something in practice that you're not doing in a game,

01:05:11.760 --> 01:05:15.679
why is that relevant? Why should we be spending our time doing that? So I kind of see

01:05:17.120 --> 01:05:21.840
the idea of making somebody code something on a whiteboard while I see some benefits to it.

01:05:23.600 --> 01:05:27.760
At what point in the game, in this game as you working on my team, are you ever going to stand

01:05:27.760 --> 01:05:31.120
in front of a whiteboard and do something like that? That's just not how we work. So why would

01:05:31.120 --> 01:05:36.959
I make somebody do that? Just one man's opinion. I know there's going to be people that are going

01:05:36.959 --> 01:05:42.239
to argue this to the death, but just one person. No, I like that. Thank you.

01:05:43.760 --> 01:05:46.239
But in saying that... They might get agreeing in the chat too.

